** related projects: http://avos.sf.net , irc #avos

This readme will help you install avlo to the av3xx. This bootloader features a config file based menu (a bt like LILO) loader. It is designed to be light and fast.
Special features:
	- use a config file to read the OS list and options
	- default OS launched after a specified time-out
	- can launch ajz or bin file
	- failsafe mode: when a problem is detected in the config file, the device is automatically put in usb mode and wait to be rebooted
	- when usb is connected, you can enter usb mode, by pressing F3
	- safe shutdown, HD spindown is perform now before stopping the device

Navigation uses UP/DOWN, ON or RIGHT to launch an OS, F3 to enter USB mode and OFF to performa a safe shutdown.


I've also provided a bin version of the avlo, if you want to test it without installing it. It's also a good way to test if the config file is good.
----------

        The installation process is the same as for the bootloader or winav. The main steps are:

1. transform the cjbm.ajz to a bin file
2. backup the original firmware
3. copy this binary and avlo to the HD
4. update to avlo
5. put back the original ajz file
----------

         Detailed installation:

1. transform the cjbm.ajz to a bin file

go on rockbox project and grab their descrambler, use this tool to transform the cjbm.ajz you use to a binary file

2. backup the original firmware

be sure to keep a copy of the cjbm.ajz file from archos on your computer

3. copy this binary and avlo to the HD

rename avlo.ajz to cjbm.ajz and put it on the root folder of the av's HD
copy the binary version of archos firmware to the same folder
copy the avlo.cfg to the same folder, don't forget to edit this file to match your config, see the section on avlo.cfg format

4. update to avlo

boot the device and do an update. At reboot you'll be in avlo

5. put back the original ajz file

for some reason you should put back the cjbm.ajz file from archos on the HD.
----------

        avlo.cfg format

First look at the sample file provided in the package. The avlo.cfg format is simple, for each OS you want to use, you need to specify the image location (image=...) and a label (label=...). Image files can be .bin or .ajz.
Example: to add an OS which binary is /linux/kernel.bin and you want to named it Linav
image=/linux/kernel.bin
label=Linav

==> quotes (") are required if you want to put spaces: to add archos FW: with the binary: /archos.bin and the label Archos FW
image=/archos.bin
label="Archos FW"

You can also add some general options:
- default: the label (not the image) of the default OS to be launched
- time-out: timeout before launching the default OS (if specifyed) => warning, this is not in seconds, numbers > 10000 should be used
- repeat: repeat rate of key
- key: passphrase used to decode ajz files
--------

	Known problems

- there can be some problem when pressing F3 to go in usb mode
- ajz decode is still a bit slow
